
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Toward a political conception of corporate responsibility: Business and society seen from a habermasian perspective
AU  - Scherer, Andreas Georg
AU  - Palazzo, Guido
Y1  - 2007/10/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.26585837
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.26585837
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 1096
EP  - 1120
VL  - 32
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We review two important schools within business and society research, which we label positivist and postpositivist corporate social responsibility (CSR). The former is criticized because of its instrumentalism and normative vacuity and the latter because of its relativism, foundationalism, and utopianism. We propose a new approach, based on Jürgen Habermas's theory of democracy, and we define the new role of the business firm as a political actor in a globalizing society.
AB  - We review two important schools within business and society research, which we label positivist and postpositivist corporate social responsibility (CSR). The former is criticized because of its instrumentalism and normative vacuity and the latter because of its relativism, foundationalism, and utopianism. We propose a new approach, based on Jürgen Habermas's theory of democracy, and we define the new role of the business firm as a political actor in a globalizing society.
