TY  - JOUR
T1  - Methodological fit in management field research
AU  - Edmondson, Amy C.
AU  - Mcmanus, Stacy E.
Y1  - 2007/10/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.26586086
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.26586086
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 1246
EP  - 1264
VL  - 32
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Methodological fit, an implicitly valued attribute of high-quality field research in organizations, has received little attention in the management literature. Fit refers to internal consistency among elements of a research project--research question, prior work, research design, and theoretical contribution. We introduce a contingency framework that relates prior work to the design of a research project, paying particular attention to the question of when to mix qualitative and quantitative data in a single research paper. We discuss implications of the framework for educating new field researchers.
AB  - Methodological fit, an implicitly valued attribute of high-quality field research in organizations, has received little attention in the management literature. Fit refers to internal consistency among elements of a research project--research question, prior work, research design, and theoretical contribution. We introduce a contingency framework that relates prior work to the design of a research project, paying particular attention to the question of when to mix qualitative and quantitative data in a single research paper. We discuss implications of the framework for educating new field researchers.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.26586086
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2007.26586086
Y2  - 2026/04/24
